{"id": "duc04-testb-0:5#17", "contents": "At the time of his death, Slepian had achieved a comfortable life as a doctor, owning a large red brick home in the suburbs. However, his journey to success was unconventional. Slepian believed that banning abortions or stopping the teaching of abortion procedures would not address the underlying issues that led to unwanted pregnancies. He felt that the country was not equipped to handle the consequences of 1.5 million unwanted children. Slepian's niece recalled that he was driven by a desire to help women and address the imperfections in society, rather than simply condemning them."}
